        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "test(durable): prove upgrade-safe workflow store lifecycle",
        "body": "Depends on:\n- #97507 (`docs: propose durable agent coordination kernel`)\n- #97508 (`feat(durable): add opt-in agent coordination kernel`)\n\nThis is the first follow-up slice for the native durable coordination work. It keeps the change focused on restart and upgrade safety so the new durable store has a clear technical foundation before higher-level coordination projections are reviewed.\n\nWhat changed:\n- Adds tests proving an existing SQLite state database can be upgraded with the durable workflow tables without rewriting unrelated state.\n- Records durable schema lifecycle in `durable_schema_migrations`.\n- Exposes the current durable schema version in store stats.\n- Rejects databases with a newer durable schema version than the running code understands.\n- Adds recovery coverage for reopening the store after a gateway restart and marking interrupted running work as lost while leaving waiting work intact.\n\nWhy this matters:\n- Durable coordination is only useful if it survives OpenClaw upgrades and gateway restarts safely.\n- This PR is intentionally storage-local and does not introduce a scheduler, worker loop, external service dependency, or AICOS-specific behavior.\n\nReview notes:\n- The branch is stacked on #97508, so the GitHub diff may include the opt-in kernel until #97508 lands.\n- The new commits after #97508 are only the restart/upgrade safety tests and schema lifecycle changes.\n- This PR can be reviewed and merged independently of the later TaskFlow/Workboard visibility slices.\n\nValidation:\n- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.unit.config.ts src/durable/recovery.test.ts src/durable/sqlite-store.test.ts`\n- `pnpm db:kysely:check`\n",
